## 1️⃣ Linux Fundamentals

Linux is the foundation for SRE operations. Understanding filesystems, processes, logs, and permissions is essential.

### File System Basics
```bash
ls -lah       # List files with permissions, sizes, and hidden files
cd /path      # Change directory
pwd           # Show current directory
mkdir newdir  # Create a directory
rm -rf folder # Remove directory recursively
Process Monitoring
top           # Real-time system monitor
htop          # Interactive process viewer
ps aux        # List all processes
kill <pid>    # Kill a process
Disk Usage
df -h         # Disk usage per filesystem
du -sh /path  # Directory size summary
Logs
journalctl -xe           # Systemd logs
tail -f /var/log/syslog  # Follow log file in real-time
Users & Permissions
whoami                       # Current user
id                            # User ID and groups
chmod 755 file                # Change file permissions
chown user:group file         # Change ownership
2️⃣ Linux Troubleshooting
High CPU Usage
top                        # Monitor CPU usage
ps aux --sort=-%cpu | head # Top CPU processes
uptime                      # Load averages
kill -9 <pid>               # Kill process if needed
Disk Full
df -h                       # Check disk usage
du -sh /*                    # Largest directories
lsof | grep deleted         # Open deleted files consuming space
Memory Leaks
free -m                     # Memory usage
top                         # Check high memory processes
ps aux --sort=-%mem | head
Hanging Processes
ps -ef | grep process_name
kill -9 <pid>

🔹 Tip: In containers/K8s, use docker stats or kubectl top pod.

3️⃣ Networking Fundamentals
TCP/IP

TCP: reliable, connection-oriented, flow control

UDP: connectionless, fast, no guarantee of delivery

Ports: Well-known 0–1023, Registered 1024–49151, Dynamic 49152–65535

Useful Commands
ping <host>
traceroute <host>
netstat -tulnp   # Shows listening ports and connections
ss -tulwn        # Modern alternative to netstat
ARP / RARP
arp -a           # List MAC addresses
# Understand Proxy ARP, Gratuitous ARP, Reverse ARP
DNS & Routing
nslookup <domain>
dig <domain> +short
route -n
ip route show
Firewalls
iptables -L   # List firewall rules
ufw status    # Simple firewall status
Troubleshooting
tcpdump -i eth0
curl -v http://example.com
nc -zv host port
